Learning Outcomes:

On successful completion of this module students should be able to:

• Identify and access hard-copy and electronic resources in library collections associated with the programme (especially ISE, QUB, and the main College library) and make regular use of WebCT for selected electronic resources;

• Choose appropriate Information Technology (IT) for different tasks and recognise specialist software to help with specific research tasks relevant to individual needs (eg Endnote, PASW);

• Submit academic work in an appropriate structure and format, with a full bibliography and consistent referencing;

• Distinguish between proper academic use of the work of others and inappropriate plagiarism;

• Conduct and present a literature review drawing on a range of relevant resources for a relevant subject of personal interest;

• Develop a coherent plan for their dissertation.


Module Learning Aims:
This module introduces generic skills used in academic research and writing. It provides an orientation to some of the resources available for studies during the programme and an analysis of academic skills involved in graduate work. It is intended to support the completion of written assignments in the taught modules and serves as early preparation for the M.Phil. dissertation


Module Content:
This is a blended-learning module combining classes/workshops at the start of term with on-line learning and personal study.

The module is taught through a sequence of class sessions in Belfast accompanied by online learning resources. The list below gives a provisional outline of the topics to be covered and the readings assigned for them. Any revisions or changes will be circulated as required and updates posted on Blackboard.

Learning Outcomes:

On successful completion of this module students should be able to:



Describe in a critical and self-critical way the field of Ecumenics;

Analyse key developments in the traditions of Christian ecumenical theologies;

Account for the theological significance of non-doctrinal factors in the shaping of religious identities;

Evaluate critically the resources (historical and contemporary) for the hermeneutics of issues in Faith and Order.




Module Learning Aims:
Module Content:
Participants attend to the methodological implications of theological ecumenicity, and, in particular; examine the historical emergence of the ecumenical movement and pivotal moments of its developing tradition; reflect on recurrent topoi of divergence (e.g., how unity is to be modelled, the ecclesial status of ecumenical instruments such as the World Council of Churches); evaluate the ecumenical potential of contemporary proposals (e.g., the Princeton Statement, or recent Faith and Order documents on both hermeneutics and ecclesiology).

Learning Outcomes:

On successful completion of this module students will be able to:

Critically analyse scholarly literature devoted to Hinduism and to Hindu-Christian comparative theology;

Evaluate critically connecting points between religion, literature and the arts in the context of classical and modern Hindu cultures, on the one hand, and between Hindu and Christian theologies, on the other.

Outline and analyze Indian religious wisdom in the Bhagavadgita, the Upanishads, devotional literature, Indian philosophy and theology;

Appraise comparatively the many ways in which Hindus and Christians visualize and theologize about the divine, and its manifestations in the world, drawing on mythic stories, images used in worship, explanations of the nature of the soul and the body in relation to the divine, and the belief in living, human embodiments of God;

Situate Hindu and Christian theological key texts not only comparatively, but also in a wider context, by attending to performative, social, visual dimensions, as well as through contemporary theological insights.



Module Learning Aims:
Module Content:
Designed as in-depth introduction to Hinduism and to Hindu-Christian comparative theology, this module studies connecting points between religion, literature and the arts in the context of classical and modern Hindu cultures, on the one hand, and between Hindu and Christian theologies, on the other. It introduces the students to Indian religious wisdom in the Bhagavadgita, the Upanishads, devotional literature, Indian philosophy and theology. The module explores comparatively the many ways in which Hindus and Christians visualize and theologize about the divine, and its manifestations in the world, drawing on mythic stories, images used in worship, explanations of the nature of the soul and the body in relation to the divine, and the belief in living, human embodiments of God. While reading Hindu and Christian theological key texts comparatively, the approach is sharpened by attention to performative, social, visual dimensions, and through contemporary theological insights.

Learning Outcomes:
On successful completion of this module students will be able to:

Describe what philosophy is and why it is part of theological studies;

Appreciate of the work of the Greek philosophers Socrates, Plato and Aristotle;

Identify and critically evaluate philosophical positions;

Reflect on their own presuppositions;

Offer a reasoned defence of some of their own basic beliefs; and

Offer an informed account of the nature and importance of the interaction between philosophy and theology.



Module Learning Aims:
Module Content:
The module is divided into two units. The first unit is Philosophy and theology and it presents many of the reasons in favour of studying philosophy, gives a survey of how philosophy might relate to theology and provides a breakdown of the main parts of philosophy.
The second unit is Greek and medieval philosophy. It explores ancient Greek philosophy as foundational for the western philosophical tradition. The unit then examines medieval philosophy which developed Greek philosophy further. The Greeks were the founders of the western philosophical tradition and the shadow of their work falls on all subsequent philosophy and brought it into direct contact with theology. The unit deals specifically with two great philosopher-theologians of the Christian tradition, Augustine (354-430 CE) and Aquinas (1225-1274 CE).
